nd space advantage give Black a strong initiative. } 11. Nc3 c6 12. d3 Bg4 13. Re1 Be7 14. f3 Be6 15. Be3 O-O { 0-1 Daneshvar,B (2401)-Idani,P (2588) IRI-ch Tehran 2021 (10) }) 8... exf3 9. Qxf3 Ne5 10. Re1 Qe7 11. Qd1 { threatening d2-d4 } 11... Bg4!? (11... Kd8 12. h3 (12. d4 { is less accurate } 12... Bg4 13. Qd2 Nxc4! { and Rxe7 isn't with check :) }) 12... Bxh3! 13. d6! { a very clever move, playing in the same spirit than 13.Rxe5 but with a difference. } (13. Rxe5 { looks tempting } 13... Qxe5 14. Bxh3 { and it looks like White has full control for the exchange, but Black has } 14... Bc5 { and d4 isn't possible ! }) (13. Bxh3 Nf3+) 13... cxd6 { now the f8-a3 diagonal is closed so White can go for } 14. Rxe5 dxe5 15. Bxh3 Qd6 16. d4! { White has to developp pieces and open lines ! } 16... Qxd4 17. Qe2 { followed by Nc3-Be3-Rd1 and full compensations. }) 12. f3 Bxf3 13. Qa4+ Kd8 14. d4 Bxg2 (14... Nfg4 { is a possible try for Black } 15. Nc3 Qb4! 16. Qxb4 Bxb4 17. dxe5 Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Nf2+ 19. Kg1 Ng4+ (19... Nd3+!? 20. Be3 Nxe1 21. Rxe1 Bxe3+ 22. Rxe3 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 { and it seems that White has better chances with his strong center. })) 15. Rxe5 Qd7 16. Qxd7+ Nxd7 17. Kxg2 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Kd7 (18... f6 19. e6 $14 c6 20. Bf4 cxd5 21. cxd5 Rc8 22. Nc3 { 1-0 Esipenko,A (2683)-Keymer,V (2717) FIDE Grand Swiss Douglas 2023 (8) }) 19. Bf4 g5 20. Be3 $13 { 1-0 Assaubayeva,B (2470)-Muzychuk,A (2525) FIDE World Rapid Team Almaty 2024 (7.5) }) 7. d3 (7. exd4 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 { is also possible, and it's all about being able to put the pawn on d4 or not for White. } 9. d3 O-O 10. Nc3 { ½-½ Wei,Y (2737)-Tan,Z (2511) Belt and Road Hunan op-A Changsha 2019 (1) } 10... e5! 11. Be3 Qd8 12. h3 c6 { and Black is fine compared to the game, the exchange of Knights helps to have more space and use the c-pawn to block the Bg2 }) 7... dxe3 { played very quickly } (7... O-O 8. exd4 Nxd4 9. Nc3 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Rb8 { not a good idea as we will see in the game ;) } 11. Bf4 a6 { ½-½ Rapport,R 