mination. }) 21. Nd6 Bxd6 22. exd6 Qxd6 (22... Nxe1 23. Qxe1 { With a big advantage for White }) 23. Re2 { threatening a5 but also to trap the knight by playing Qc3-Red2 ! }) 20. Qxe1 Qc8 21. Nf3! { with a total domination. Black rooks are passive, c7 and a5 are hanging, the Nc6 doesn't have much squares to go... } (21. Nxc6 bxc6 22. Na7 { looks tempting but after } 22... Qe6 23. d5 cxd5 24. Bxd5 Qa6 25. Nc6 Rbc8 26. Qxa5 Qxa5 27. Nxa5 { Black has the very strong } 27... Bg5! 28. Bxg5 hxg5 29. Rd2 Re1 { with good counterplay. } { [%csl Yh2][%cal Bf5e4] })) 19... Nxe1 20. Qxe1 Nd4 21. Nfxd4 exd4 22. Nxd4 Bg6 23. Qxa5 Bg5 24. Bxg5 hxg5 25. Qd2 { with a good advantage but not decisive :) }) 18. d4! { played "a tempo" by Ding ! } 18... e4 { the only move } (18... exd4 19. Bf4! Rc8 20. Nfxd4 Nxd4 21. Qxd4 Nc5 22. Nxc7! { wins easly. }) 19. Ng1 { stepping back to jump better ! The Knight is heading to f4 } 19... Nb6 20. Qc3!? { Very natural } 20... Bf6 { trying to delay the d4-d5 push } (20... f5 { was the best choice according to the machine, but it's a very weakening move, opening the king, closing the Bg6 and giving up the e5 and e6 squares } 21. f3!) 21. Qc2 { stepping out from the Bf6 scope. } 21... a4 22. Ne2 { Black position is hopeless, all pieces are too passive. } { [%cal Be2f4] } 22... Bg5?! { a mistake but it's totally understandable not to allow the Knight installation on f4 } (22... Na5 23. c5 Nbc4 24. Nf4 Bf5 25. Bf1 { was the best continuation for Black but here after } 25... c6 26. Bxc4 Nxc4 27. Qxc4 cxb5 28. Qxb5 Bd7 29. Qc4 { and d5 coming, i don't see any hope for Black. } { [%cal Bd4d5] }) 23. Nf4! Bxf4 24. Bxf4 { [%csl Yc7,Yb6,Yc6] } 24... Rc8 { 13 } 25. Qc3 { The Queen's dance continue ! threatening d5 and depriving a5 and e5 squares to the Nc6 } { [%csl Ye5,Ya5,Yc6][%cal Bc3a5,Bc3h8,Bd4d5] } 25... Nb8?! { Desperation, Gukesh is suffering since too much time and under time pressure try to give material to organize his pieces. } 26. d5! { Ding doesn'